Design and développementLe S. 51 is a seaplane sesquiplan car. Its V8 engine Hispano-Suiza 8A, 300-horsepower, mounted on two struts between the hull and the wing higher, resulting in a pusher propeller bladed. It was also equipped with floats stabilizations to the ends of the lower wing."Artwork of Savoia S. 51 by Hideaki Ozawa". RAIS basa later the design of the hull of the S. 58 of hunting in 1924 on the S. 51.Green and Swanborough, p. 527.
History opérationnelleToutes the sources agree that Italy joined the S. 51 in the Trophy Schneider 1922 with two Macchi M. 17, and that the three Italian aircraft ran off against the Supermarine Sea Lion II british who won the race. But, the sources are contradictory when in the career of the S. 51.Some sourcesAviation History: Schneider Trophy Races and Vašiček, Aviation History, September 2002, p. 34. claim that the S. 51 crashed during the race, killing its driver.Schneider Trophy Races Archived February 19, 2009, at the Wayback Machine. Another assumes that the S. 51 suffered damage in a road accident in pre-race, which forced him to give up because its nacelle engine began to separate from the upper wing during the race; however, this source does not say that the plane crashed."Schneider Trophy 6th Edition August 1922". "Society of Air Racing Historians: Schneider Cup Races." Italian Wikipedia Savoia-Marchetti S. 51 others argue that the S-51 finished the race with an average speed of 230.93 kilometers per hour (143.41 miles per hour) and a final time of 1 hour 36 minutes and 54 seconds, thus reaching the second place behind the Sea Lion II but ahead of both M. 17.Some sources claim that the S. 51 had a career after the race. A source"IPMS Racing & Record Aircraft SIG - Record List". states that on 28 December 1922 the S. 51 set a speed record pourhydravions to 280.155 kilometres (174.080&#x20;mi) per hour.
